🔹 Problem: Product of Array Except Self
Given an array nums, return an array answer such that:

answer[i] = product of all elements except nums[i]

👉 Constraints:

❌ No division allowed (important!)
Must run in O(n)

🧠 1. Brute Force Approach
💡 Idea:

For each index, multiply all other elements.

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1) (excluding output)

✅ Code:
vector<int> productExceptSelf(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();
    vector<int> result(n, 1);

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int prod = 1;
        for(int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if(i != j) {
                prod *= nums[j];
            }
        }
        result[i] = prod;
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Very slow for large input
Recomputes products repeatedly
Not acceptable in interviews

📌 When to use:
Only to explain baseline

⚡ 2. Better Approach (Using Division)
💡 Idea:
Compute total product
Divide by each element

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)

✅ Code:
vector<int> productExceptSelf(vector<int>& nums) {
    int total = 1;
    for(int num : nums) total *= num;

    vector<int> result;
    for(int num : nums) {
        result.push_back(total / num);
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons (CRITICAL):
❌ Fails when zeros are present
❌ Division not allowed (as per problem)
❌ Precision issues (in some languages)

📌 When to use:
Only if interviewer allows division (rare)

🚀 3. Optimal Approach (Prefix + Suffix Arrays)
💡 Idea:
prefix[i] = product of elements before i
suffix[i] = product of elements after i

Then:

answer[i] = prefix[i] * suffix[i]

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)

✅ Code:
vector<int> productExceptSelf(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();

    vector<int> prefix(n, 1), suffix(n, 1), result(n);

    for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        prefix[i] = prefix[i - 1] * nums[i - 1];
    }

    for(int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
        suffix[i] = suffix[i + 1] * nums[i + 1];
    }

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        result[i] = prefix[i] * suffix[i];
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Uses extra space O(n)
Can be optimized further

📌 When to use:
When clarity is more important than optimization

🚀🚀 4. Best Optimal (Space Optimized)
💡 Idea:
Use result array to store prefix
Then multiply with suffix on the fly

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n) ✅
Space: O(1) (excluding output)

✅ Code:
vector<int> productExceptSelf(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();
    vector<int> result(n, 1);

    // prefix
    for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        result[i] = result[i - 1] * nums[i - 1];
    }

    // suffix
    int suffix = 1;
    for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        result[i] *= suffix;
        suffix *= nums[i];
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Slightly tricky to understand at first
Requires careful explanation in interview

📌 When to use:
Best solution for interviews
Meets all constraints
